### User:
How do you align a row of divs to the right using flex in css?  Show me an example.

### Response:


To align a row of divs to the right using flex in CSS, you can use the `flex-direction` property with the value `row`. Here's an example:

```css
.container {
 display: flex;
 flex-direction: row; /* Align the rows to the right */
 justify-content: center; /* Center the elements within each row */
}

.div1, .div2, .div3 {
 width: 50%;
 background-color: #f2f2f2;
 padding: 10px;
 text-align: center;
 margin: 10px;
 border: 1px solid #ddd;
}
```

In this example, the `container` class uses `flex` to align its contents to the right. The `justify-content` property is set to `center` to distribute the elements evenly within each row. Within each div, we use `text-align: center` and `margin` to center the content horizontally. Finally, we add a border with some dashed lines to create some visual separation between the elements.
